contents.body:
### **ðŸŽ¨ Oopsies & Fixes â€“ Common Mistakes in Antechamber Tasks ðŸ˜…** Welcome to the crash course in what *not* to do! ðŸ˜… Below are the most common mistakes spotted during reviews, turned into friendly rules to help you level up your task game. Follow these tips and your tasks will be pure gold! ðŸŒŸðŸŽ¨ Letâ€™s make every task shine! ðŸŒŸ Hereâ€™s a handy guide to the most frequent slip-ups and how you can totally avoid them. You got this! ðŸ’ªðŸ§ 

Category

What Went Wrong

How to Get It Right

â±ï¸ Not Enough User Prompts

Uh-oh! The task had fewer than 10 user prompts. (not total turns, just user prompts)

Every task must include exactly 10 user prompts at least. Keep the convo flowing until you hit 10 turns! ðŸ’¬âž¡ï¸ This means you will have written 10 prompts.

ðŸ”§ Assistant Responded with Text Instead of a Tool

Instead of triggering a tool (like looking something up or scheduling), the assistant replied with text. ðŸ“„

If the user asks for something that requires action or info retrieval, go for the tool! âš™ï¸

Unless the assistant needs more context, then itâ€™s valid to answer with a follow up question.

ðŸ§© Incorrect or Hallucinated Tool Parameters

The assistant used the right tool, but oops! missed or botched a parameter (like leaving out a query, wrong location, etc.).

Double-check your tool fields! Make sure you're passing in everything it needs to work magic. ðŸª„

Make sure the tool parameters were not hallucinated i.e. the parameters were retrieved from either the system prompt, a separate tool call, or were clarified by the user in a prompt.

â˜‘ï¸ Empty Checkbox Section

Everything is perfect, BUT,  checkboxes were NOT touched. 

You gotta pick at least one checkbox to confirm the tool was used properly. No skipping! âœ…âœ…âœ…

ðŸ•µï¸â€â™€ï¸ Critique is Missing or Too Vague

"Tool error" isnâ€™t enough. ðŸ˜­The critique didnâ€™t explain what actually went wrong or name the tool/problem.

Be specific! Name the error type, mention the tool name, and call out exactly what went wrong. ðŸ’¡

ðŸ§  Reasoning Not in Required Format

The reasoning was confusing, super short, or didnâ€™t follow the expected structure.

Format it like this: 

The user would like to [action]. To fulfill the userâ€™s request, I will use the [tool_name] tool with the [parameter] parameter set to "value".

Example: The user would like to open a photo of Bill. To fulfill the users request, I will use the photos_open_target tool with the target parameter set to â€œBillâ€.âœ¨

ðŸš« No Error Marked When There Was One

The tool clearly failed, but no error tag was applied. ðŸ˜±

Always check tool outputs. If it failed, tag it! 

ðŸŽ­ Off-Tone or Personality Fail

CB didnâ€™t stay in character or strayed from the vibe (e.g., too robotic, too generic, too stiff).

Keep it fun and friendly! Stick to the persona in the system promptâ€”whether itâ€™s a goofy artist, cool mom, or anyone else. ðŸŽ¨ðŸ§‘â€ðŸŽ¤

ðŸŒ Ignored Categories or Settings

CB didnâ€™t follow the assigned task category, used the wrong location, or ignored system settings. ðŸ“

Check EVERYTHING! Stay aligned with the assigned location, category, and language at all times. ðŸŒðŸ“‹
### **Rule 1 ðŸ”Ÿ: Complete the Conversation** **You must write exactly 10 user prompts.** Some tasks ended early or stopped at 8â€“9 turns. But every Antechamber task must contain 10 user prompts, at least. Thatâ€™s the magic minimum. If the userâ€™s request ends quickly, keep the flow going with natural topic transitionsÂ  task switching is part of the fun! ðŸ”„ðŸ—£ï¸ ### **Rule 2 ðŸ› ï¸: Trigger Tools (Unless Text Makes More Sense)** **Use tools as much as possible â€” but sometimes a text response is the right call.** The goal is to rely heavily on tools when the user prompt calls for it ; searching for products, booking, location info, etc. But there are cases where a tool just isn't appropriate. If the assistant canâ€™t perform the action (like placing an order) or the user's request is vague, a friendly and informative text response is best. Balance is key! ðŸ§°ðŸ’¬ ### **Rule 3 â˜‘ï¸: Donâ€™t Skip the Checkbox** **Always mark the tool validation checkboxes.** Even when a tool call is triggered, the validation section was sometimes left blank. That means we canâ€™t tell if the model did it right or not. Always mark at least one checkbox to show you reviewed the tool use. âœ…ðŸ§ ### **Rule 4 â“: Ask First, Act Second** **If the user didnâ€™t give enough detail, donâ€™t jump the gun.** Some tool calls were made without knowing what the user actually wanted. Don't assume; ask a follow-up question before making the call. Otherwise, you risk giving the wrong output or using the wrong tool. ðŸ¤”ðŸ›‘ ### **Rule 5 ðŸ—‚ï¸: Fill Tool Parameters Carefully** **Make sure the tool parameters match the userâ€™s request. Make sure the tool parameters were not hallucinated i.e. the parameters were retrieved from either the system prompt, a separate tool call, or were clarified by the user in a prompt.** Wrong country, vague query, or missing fields? Big no-no. Read the user prompt, review the context, and provide every necessary input to the tool call. If youâ€™re not sure, go back and clarify first. ðŸŒðŸ” ### **Rule 6 ðŸ“‹: Write Reasoning in the Right Format** **Stick to the structured format to clearly explain your decision.** Format it like this: The user would like to action. To fulfill the userâ€™s request, I will use the tool_name tool with the parameter parameter set to "value". âœ… Example: The user would like to open a photo of Bill. To fulfill the userâ€™s request, I will use the photos_open_target tool with the target parameter set to "Bill". âœ¨ Use present tense, match the system prompt tone, and be clear about intent and tool usage. ðŸ’¡ ### **Rule 7 ðŸ§ : Explain the Critique Properly** **Donâ€™t be vague.** Just saying "wrong output" or "tool error" isnâ€™t enough. Your critique should explain what went wrong, what tool was used (or missing), and how it could have been done better. Be the helpful expert you wish you had. ðŸ§¾ðŸ” ### **Rule 8 ðŸš©: Tag the Error!** **Use the correct error type from the list below.** If a tool fails or is misused, tag the issue accurately so we can track patterns and improve. Here's your cheat sheet: â­ **extra_param_predicted**: The model added an argument that wasnâ€™t included in the tool definition. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Should not have used argument format for search_file.â€* â­ **param_type_inconsistent**: Type mismatch in a parameter. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Argument target should be a string, but an integer was provided.â€* â­ **param_not_defined**: Used a parameter thatâ€™s not defined in the tool. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Tool call involves album, which isnâ€™t part of the definition.â€* â­ **required_param_missing**: Forgot to provide a required argument. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Didnâ€™t include target in the photos_open_album tool call.â€* â­ **enum_not_respected**: Gave a value outside of the accepted options. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*paragraph_style should be from enum, but got text body instead.â€* â­ **wrong_tool_selected**: Used the wrong tool â€” or hallucinated one. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Used photos_open_destination instead of photos_open_album.â€* â­ **wrong_param_value**: Incorrect or hallucinated parameter values. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*The notes parameter should have had multiple tags, not just one.â€* â­ **no_tool_triggered**: Replied in text when a tool call was needed. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Shouldâ€™ve used notes_add_tags_to_notes, but gave a plain answer.â€* â­ **tool_over_triggered**: Triggered a tool when text wouldâ€™ve been better. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Should have asked a follow-up, but used notes_set_paragraph_style instead.â€* â­ **parallel_calls_missing**: Needed more than one tool call at once. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Should have called get_weather and show_clothing_ideas together.â€* â­ **unsatisfactory_summary**: Misrepresented the tool output. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Missed details, hallucinated, or ignored one of the results.â€* â­ **tool_call_not_parsable**: Model generated a broken tool call. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Contains , but didnâ€™t parse properly.â€* â­ **is_error**: The task contains an error being corrected later. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Used for recovery tasks. Still critique + tag appropriately.â€* â­ **others**: Something weird happened. âž¡ï¸ â€œ*Explain it clearly in the critic comments.â€* â­ **no_issues**: Everything looks great! âž¡ï¸ â€œ*You can leave the critic comments empty.â€* ### **Rule 9 ðŸŽ­: Match the Vibe** **Refine assistant responses to match the tone set by the system prompt.** You don't have control over the assistantâ€™s personality,Â  the model generates the initial replies. But you *do* have the power to refine them! âœ¨ If the system prompt says the assistant is a peppy artist or a chill local, then keep that tone throughout the whole conversation.! ðŸŒˆðŸ—£ï¸ ### **Rule 10 ðŸ“: Stick to Tools, Categories & Settings** **Make sure your task reflects the systemâ€™s assigned tools, category, and system settings.** Everything you need is at the top of the task. Donâ€™t stray from the assigned tools, ignore the selected category, or forget the specific setup (like location or available services). Stick to the script, and if anything seems off or inconsistent, just refine to align! ðŸ§­ðŸ“¦ Keep in mind: * Only the model can toggle **WiFi** (users canâ€™t!). If WiFi is off and the assistant needs internet for a tool call, it must turn WiFi on first. * **Cellular doesnâ€™t provide data** in this setup,Â  tools that require the internet wonâ€™t work unless WiFi is active. * The **system prompt** always takes priority. If the system prompt says WiFi is off, but the tool requires it, the model should act accordingly (turn it on or reply that it canâ€™t proceed). * Donâ€™t define personas that contradict the available tools. For example, if no calendar tools are available, donâ€™t make your agent a "calendar expert". Thatâ€™s setting them up to fail. ðŸ™ˆ

contents.question: **Youâ€™re crafting a task and realize it has 45 total turns but only 8 user prompts. What should you do before submitting?**

choices.answer: A) Submit the task â€” 45 turns is enough context
B) Trim the assistant responses and submit with 8 user prompts
C) Keep going until you reach exactly 10 user prompts.

contents.explanation: Explanation: Every Antechamber task must have exactly 10 user prompts â€” no more, no less. If youâ€™re at 8, keep building! You can creatively switch topics if needed, just make sure the task remains engaging and complete. ðŸŽ¯ðŸ› ï¸

contents.question: **A user asks for help choosing a birthday gift, but doesnâ€™t specify for whom or what kind. The model immediately triggers a product search. Whatâ€™s the right move?**

choices.answer: A) Leave it as-is â€” guessing is fine
B) Penalize and select a text response, a text follow-up question should be done before the tool call
C) Just swap the tool call for a better guess

contents.explanation: Explanation: If thereâ€™s not enough detail to use a tool meaningfully, the assistant should first ask a polite follow-up. Only once the info is available should a tool be triggered. Think before you click! ðŸ’¬ðŸ› ï¸

contents.question: #### Think as a reviewer: The tool call is correct, but the contributor forgot to mark the checkboxes confirming it. What now?

choices.answer: B) Leave it, itâ€™s not critical
C) Mark the checkboxes confirming correct tool usage

contents.explanation: You must check the validation boxes â€” even if the tool call is flawless. This tells reviewers you reviewed the tool behavior. Skipping it = incomplete work. â˜‘ï¸âœ…

contents.question: #### The assistant triggered a tool, but key info (like the type of paint or location) was never clarified with the user. What should you do?

choices.answer: A) Assume and fill in the blanks
B) Remove the tool call and choose a text response to get  a clarification request instead
C) Replace the tool with something else entirely

contents.explanation: Explanation: Tools arenâ€™t fortune-tellers. If the assistant doesnâ€™t ask for critical parameters, contributors must rewrite the turn to add that friendly clarifying step. ðŸ”ðŸ‘‚

contents.question: #### The assistant used a valid tool but did not provide a required parameter.  What error does this represent?
contents.explanation: Explanation: The tool requires a specific data type â€” in this case, a string. Using null breaks the schema and leads to failure. Always double-check parameters! ðŸ§ªðŸ§¾

contents.question: #### Whatâ€™s the correct reasoning format ?

choices.answer: A) â€œI used the tool because the user asked.â€
B) â€œThe model used (tool) to do (action).â€
C) â€œThe user would like to (do something). To fulfill the userâ€™s request, I will use the (tool)  with the (parameter)  set to (value).â€

contents.explanation: Explanation: That third one? ðŸ‘‘ Gold standard. Itâ€™s the required format and helps everyone understand exactly why and how the tool was triggered. Clear, structured, and easy to follow. ðŸŽ¯ðŸ› ï¸

contents.question: #### If a tool was required but the model just gave a plain text response instead, whatâ€™s the correct error type?
contents.explanation: Explanation: If the model replies in text when a tool shouldâ€™ve been used (like for a product search or translation), thatâ€™s a no_tool_triggered error.  ðŸ””ðŸ‘€

contents.question: #### The model gets the right tool call and sees the tool output, but then misrepresents it when summarizing. What error should be tagged?
contents.explanation: Explanation: This is a classic unsatisfactory_summary. Whether itâ€™s inventing details or omitting key info, the model must accurately reflect tool output in summaries. If it messes up? Call it out! ðŸ“‰ðŸ§

contents.question: #### Youâ€™re working on a task where the system prompt defines the assistant as a cheerful dance instructor, but the assistant sounds robotic. What should you do?

choices.answer: A) Let it be â€” tone doesnâ€™t matter
B) Refine responses to match the system promptâ€™s personality
C) Change the system prompt to match the assistant

contents.explanation: Explanation: You canâ€™t change the system prompt or persona, but you can refine assistant responses to match the expected tone. Stick to the script â€” literally. ðŸŽ­ðŸ•º

contents.question:
#### The system settings clearly says: â€œWiFi- ON Cellular is ON. Location Services are enabled.â€ The user asks the assistant to â€œlook up directions to a nearby galleryâ€. What should the assistant do before using the GET_DIRECTIONS tool.

Select ALL that apply

choices.answer: A) Clarify where the userâ€™s starting point / current location is (origin) - using either **get_current_location (if tool is activated)** or asking the user for their location.
B) Clarify which gallery the user is looking to go to (destination)

C) After obtaining information about the userâ€™s location and destination - use the **search_place** tool or **convert_place_id_lat_long_address** to obtain place_idâ€™s as inputs to the **get_directions** tool

contents.question: A turn is labeled as "State Dependency," but the only thing the user does is ask, "Is my WiFi on?" What is the issue?

choices.answer: The task does not qualify as "State Dependency."

contents.hint: State Dependency requires that a tool call fails because of a system state, like WiFi being off. Simply checking a setting does not qualify.

contents.question: The model uses a `search_events` tool to look for active weather alerts. What error should be flagged?
After modifying the assistant's final text response for clarity, you forget to apply an error tag. What error type should you have used?

A model is expected to correct its failed tool call on itâ€™s own (not have the response refined by the user) based on a follow-up prompt from the user. What category is this scenario best labeled as?
In the system prompt, the assistant is instructed not to use settings-related tools. The assistant still uses `set_wifi_status`. What error should be flagged?
The model retrieves system settings using `get_system_settings`. Before this, no settings were mentioned in the system prompt. Should the model be expected to know that WiFi is off?

choices.answer: No - The model does **not** know system settings unless they are retrieved by tool or stated in the system prompt.

contents.question: The model returns a calendar event using the correct tool, but it hallucinates the eventâ€™s `end_time`, which was not included in the tool call. What error should be flagged?
The model receives a `tool_response` and immediately calls another tool using the wrong `place_id` taken from a previous result. What kind of error is this?
A model answers a userâ€™s vague request by asking a clarifying question instead of a tool call. Should this be flagged?
If the model uses a tool correctly and the tool response is perfect, I can still edit the final natural language response for tone **without** applying any error tag.

choices.answer: True - it is okay to make minor changes to model responses without tagging errors
False - If you change the final assistant response in any way, you must apply an appropriate error tag, most often `unsatisfactory_summary`.

contents.question: A task is considered "Infeasible Tool Use" if the model *could have* answered the prompt with tools, but didnâ€™t.
"Error Recovery" requires that the model fail first, and then be guided to fix the issue through follow-up user prompts.
A model is allowed to make assumptions based on system settings without checking them via tools if the user asks about device status.

choices.answer: The model must **use** `get_system_settings` unless the setting is already provided in the system prompt.

contents.question: A model failing to follow a behavioral instruction in the system prompt (like â€œalways confirm before deleting eventsâ€) is considered a valid issue and must be corrected, even if tool parameters were correct.
#### The user says theyâ€™re looking for concert tickets, but the model immediately triggers a `calendar_create_event` tool call. Whatâ€™s the correct fix?

choices.answer: A) Leave the tool call as-is.
B) Mark  a text response was needed asking for date, artist, or preferences, then choose the right tool

contents.explanation: Explanation: This is a tool misuse. The correct response would involve clarifying the userâ€™s intent first and using a shopping or event-related tool if available â€” not calendar-related tools. ðŸ—“ï¸âŒðŸŽ«

contents.question: #### The system settings say WiFi is OFF. What needs to be done for Wifi to turn ON?

choices.answer: A) I can tell the model Wifi is ON now
B) The model must use **set**\_**system_settings** or **set_wifi_status** tool to turn Wifi ON
C) The model can turn WiFi on without using a tool

contents.explanation: Explanation: Some tools require WiFi specifically, even if Cellular is available. The model must either turn on WiFi using get_system_settings tools.

contents.question: #### The assistant receives tool response with 5 product suggestions. It summarizes only 1, misstates the price, and ignores the others. What error tag applies?
contents.explanation: Explanation: All relevant output must be represented accurately. Misrepresenting tool results, whether by omission or hallucination, leads to unsatisfactory_summary. Be thorough! ðŸ§¾ðŸ”

contents.body: #### The user says: **"** Before you get directions, book lunch plans in my calendar at Sappe?" (Note: The model already has place_id and location detail for Sappe from prior turns) The model triggers this tool call:

contents.question:
Whatâ€™s wrong with this response from the model?\
\
Select ALL that apply

choices.answer: A) The model hallucinated the **calendar_id** to add the event to (The model did not confirm which calendar the event should be added to)
B) The model hallucinated the **start_datetime** of the calendar event (The model did not confirm when the calendar event should start)
C) The model hallucinated the **end_datetime** of the calendar event (The model did not confirm when the calendar event should end)

contents.question: **Is the following a tool call, tool response, or text response?\ \ **
True/False: Tool Responses should be critiqued / error tagged

choices.answer: True: Tool Responses should be refined / corrected
False: Tool Responses canâ€™t be corrected or critiqued, and if something is wrong with tool response, the earlier tool call should potentially be fixed instead.
